value.value: A treated form of sludge, sometimes used as a fertilizer in agriculture.
A solid or gel in motor oil caused by the oil gelling or solidifying, usually at temperatures lower than 100deg C.

Sediment that accumulates in the flat or very gently sloping areas of the deep ocean basin floor. The three main types of deep marine sediment, also known as pelagic sediment, are siliceous oozes, calcareous oozes, and red clays.

definition.value: Sediment which has increased levels of one or more chemical compounds.
Organically enriched sediment which has increased levels of petroleum.
A portion of contaminated soil is a portion of soil with elevated levels of some contaminant.
"contaminant" is more of a disposition - any material entity can be a contaminant in particular circumstances.
Soil which has elevated concentrations of creosote.
Mud which has elevated concentrations of arsenic.
Revise adjacent to. Consider sampled stream sediment. Dry stream sediment.
Mud which has no or neglible concentrations of dissolved oxygen.

value.value: The liquid produced when water percolates through any permeable material. It can contain either dissolved or suspended material, or usually both.

definition.value: Soil which has elevated concentrations of chromate.
Soil which has elevated concentrations of xylene.
Coal mine lake sediment is lake sediment which covers the bottom of a coal mine lake.
Water which has physicochemical properties that have been determined by the processes occuring in a sea or ocean.
This definition refers to water that is actually in a sea or ocean. This water may have a wide range of salinity levels.
Coastal sea water is sea water that is adjacent to a coast.

The limits of what qualifies as "adjacent to" vary greatly. This should be defined on a data level and is left intentionally fuzzy here. The label is "coastal sea water" rather than "coastal water" as some large lakes are often said to have coasts.
Mud which is part of an estuary.

value.value: A solid environmental material which is formed by the replacement of organic substances (including those in soils and sediments) with mineral material.
Manure which has been derived from the aerobically decomposed remnants of organic materials.

definition.value: Organically enriched sediment which has increased levels of naphthalene.
Organically enriched sediment which has increased levels of nitrobenzene.

value.value: Straw or other material strewn in an animal's enclosure (e.g. a stable) for it to sleep on and to absorb its faeces and urine.

definition.value: Water ice which has formed by the freezing of sea water.

value.value: In the United States, NOAA sea ice operations does not include superstructure icing as being sea ice. In sea ice operations however, sea ice is any form of ice found at sea which has originated from the freezing of sea water. It presents the main kind of floating ice encountered at sea. Except where it forms ridges, sea ice is up to a few metres thick, in which respect it differs from shelf ice.  Sea ice may be discontinuous pieces (ice floes) moved on the ocean surface by wind and currents (pack ice), or a motionless sheet attached to the coast (land-fast ice). In brief, it forms first as lolly ice (frazil crystals), thickens into sludge, and coagulates into sheet ice, pancake ice, or into floes of various shapes and sizes. Thereafter, sea ice may develop into pack ice and/or become a form of pressure ice.  Sea ice less than one year old is called first-year ice. Perennial ice is sea ice that survives at least one summer. It may be subdivided into second-year ice and multi-year ice, where multiyear ice has survived at least two summers.

definition.value: Organically enriched sediment which has increased levels of cis-dichloroethane.
Chemically-enriched sediment which has increased levels of organic compounds.
Chemically-enriched sediment which has increased levels of inorganic compounds.
Saline lake sediment is sediment which covers the bottom of a saline lake.
